The poem starts sad and ends happy by means of a single
stunning metaphor.

Line 1, 'When'. This is not what he is experiencing at this
moment. It is 'recollected in tranquillity', as Wordsworth
said. Shakespeare often does this: there are ten sonnets
beginning 'when', exacerbating the compositor's shortage of
outsize capital Ws and forcing him to use VV or sometimes an
italic W.

The first four lines describe the speaker's actions as an
observer might. The next four are psychological, describing
his inner thoughts.

Line 7, 'Desiring this man's art'. Not what an aristocrat
would desire, or at least admit to desiring. Learning a
craft is not aristocratic. Compare the aristocrat who, asked
if he could play the violin, answered &quot;I don't know: I have
never tried&quot;.

Line 8. Remarkable how what you can actually do, once you
can do it well, comes to seem less desirable than the things
other people can do.

Line 10 prepares for the leap and at line 11 we have
lift-off - a marvellous effect. The lark is originally a
bird of the steppes. It nests in open ground and takes off
at dawn, not directly from its nest, singing as it goes and
soaring vertically until it becomes very hard to pick out
by eye, though it can still be clearly heard. It was common
until recently but is now increasingly rare.

Line 12, 'sullen'. Cognate with 'sole' and 'solitary',
implying morose ill-humour in people. Often also transferred
to other things, but here it looks more like a metaphor than
a specialised meaning. I suggest the earth is damp and cold
after the night, and also shaded because the rising sun has
not yet penetrated to the flat ground where the lark nests.

Line 14, 'scorn'. Picks up (I suggest) 'despising' from line
9 and turns it round: he now despises not himself but the
rest of the world.

'state'. This word has appeared three times. In line 2 it
means 'situation', the speaker's position in the world. In
line 10 it means 'state of mind'. In line 14 it comes back
close to its meaning in line 2, but also picks up ideas of
grandeur or stateliness from the kings - a good state this
time, when at the beginning it was wretched.

