When I am out of luck, and out of favour with society, /
I sit on my own, mourning my loneliness /
and pester God, who is not listening, with useless prayers that will
not be answered /
and think about myself and condemn the situation to which I am
doomed; /
I think of people with better prospects and wish I was like them, /
as handsome as A, as popular as B; /
I wish I had C's skill or D's comprehensive knowledge, /
and the talents I value least are those I have most of. /
But when, thinking this way, I come nearest to contempt for
myself, /
sometimes I happen to think about you, and when I do that my mental
condition /
(like a lark that flies up at dawn /
from the gloomy ground) praises God in the sky. /
For when I remember that you love me, I feel so rich /
that I would not dream of exchanging my position for that of a
king. /

_________________________

***This is without a doubt my favorite of the sonnets!--and so I'm too
humbled to even try to produce a paraphrase of my own. The only
quibble I would have with Robert's fine paraphrase would be his
&quot;praises God in the sky&quot; for the poet's &quot;sings hymns at heaven's
gate.&quot; I take &quot;heaven's gate&quot; simply to be the point of ingress for
the day--that is, the dawn again--which seems to be supported by
*Cymbeline*'s &quot;Hark! hark! the lark at heaven's gate sings,
And Phoebus 'gins arise.&quot; I'd just have it that the lark sings at
sunrise rather than praises God in the sky. Does anyone know of
other, non-Shakespearean, usages of &quot;Heaven's gate&quot; which might lie
behind Shakespeare's usage of the term?

***Hm. If the day's ingress comes via heaven's gate, does the day's
egress go via hell's gate? Well, come to think of it, I *have* had
days like that...

