All but one of the eleven instances of 'Fortune' in
the Sonnets are personified as opposed to 'fortune'
in the plays which almost always means luck or fate.

Elizabeth was 'Lady Fortune' in the sense that she
arbitrarily promoted and demoted favorites by
redistributing honors, titles and monopolies. She
enriched Dudley and Hatton and ruined Oxford,
Raleigh, Walsingham, Essex and others.

Since Southampton is the logical dedicatee of the
Sonnets (Rowse's theory that Mr. H.W. is William Hervey
is the most robust) it would mean the Sonnets were
written at Court.

O, for my sake do you with Fortune chide,
The guilty goddess of my harmful deeds,
That did not better for my life provide
Than public means which public manners breeds

The last two lines reflect the fact that Bacon, while
waiting for the promised appointment--promised
by Elizabeth but unfortunately not promised by
Burghley--had to take cases from the public and
argue them in the public courts accepting money
from members of the public.

Courtiers didn't do 'public work.'

Sonnet 111 reflects the fact that Southampton and
Essex furiously lobbied the Queen to give Bacon an
office:

A few months later Sir Robert Cecil attempted to persuade
Essex to be content with the Solicitor-General's office for
Bacon, which 'might be of easier digestion to her Majesty.'

'Digest me no digestions,' Essex angrily answered,
'for the Attorneyship for Francis is that I must have; and
in that I will spend all my power, might, authority, and amity,
and with tooth and nail defend and procure the same for
him against whom soever; and whosoever getteth this
office out of my hands for any other, before he have it,
it shall cost him the coming by.' In Queen Elizabeth,
J.E. Neale, Harcourt Brace.

Essex and Southampton were so obnoxious that in
the end the Queen told them to 'shut up and go to
bed' and she awarded the offices to Egerton and Coke.

Edgerton, twenty years older than Bacon, was a
working lawyer with a brilliant legal mind, after
the mature Bacon one of the finest lawyers
England ever produced while Coke, a klutz at law,
was assured advancement simply because he was
the Cecil protege.

As Stonehouse notes:

