&gt; wrong.

"/>

***Could be. But why &quot;heaven's gate&quot; here? In the Marlowe quote,
it's obvious that Learning is storming the palace of the gods; that
gate makes sense in the progression of ideas and images. Here, it's
less clear. Are we to consider that the welkin in general is a &quot;gate&quot;
to heavenly feelings? The lark, and the poet's spirits, could be
aloft, and indeed aloft in the heavens, without having to be at a gate
to be elevated. I see it more that the poet's spirit stands at the
eastern &quot;gate&quot; between night and day (perhaps I am influenced by 28)
at which gate each major section (night/day) of the 24 hours makes its
first appearance, and that, as the winging lark sings presumably for
joy at first light, so does the Poet's &quot;state&quot; sing joyful hymns of
thanksgiving at the spiritual sunrise brought about by thinking of the
addressee.

