I am no more confident about that than anyone else
(except Paul) is here. I am inclined to think that
Southampton is probably the main contender (mainly
on the basis of the *V&amp;A* and *Lucrece* dedications)
but I have more recently wondered whether the first
seventeen (on stylometric grounds) and some of the
later ones might not have been addressed to William
Herbert instead.

I am quite convinced by Don Foster's argument that
&quot;Mr.W.H.&quot; refers to the *poet* rather than to either
an inspirer or procurer of the sonnets, however. The
initials can, of course, correspond to whatever name
he happened to be using at that time.

My main candidate for the &quot;Dark Lady&quot; currently is
a defrocked French nun called either Ide du Vault or
Madame Vallereine, who was employed at Burley on the
Hill at the same time as the Monsieur le Doux I have
just been discussing with 'Buffalo'.

Finally, I think it possible that the so-called
'dedication' at the start of the Sonnets is written
apparently by Thorpe but actually on behalf of
Southampton or Pembroke (either of whom could have
thought of themselves as adventurers &quot;setting forth&quot;
in 1609), the Sonnets and The Lover's Complaint
having been printed primarily as a gift for the
poet himself.

