I get the feeling of &quot;time's winged chariot&quot;, but that is
because of the weekly deadline, which does not apply to the
rest of the world!

Now, first, an art IS a craft, in the origin of the idea.
The &quot;Art of Love&quot; is a technical manual, as is the Art of
Poetry. In the Middle Ages, arts were kept secret: 'The Art
and Mystery of Shoemaking'. Hence the Mystery plays: the
shepherds did the Nativity, the fishermen the Flood, the
carpenters the Crucifixion. Hence also Abhorson's protest in
Measure for Measure when people run down the art of the
executioner: 'I say, it is a Mystery!' (Albert Pierrepoint
in his memoirs calls it 'the craft'.) The idea that 'art'
was one thing and 'craft' a distinctly lower one may be no
older than the 19th century.

Secondly, it was not an aristocratic thing, at least when
taken seriously. Certainly Sidney (Apology for Poetry)
thinks his own attachment to poetry is a thing to be
concealed, or treated lightly with aristocratic disdain
('sprezzatura'). He accepts ambition in his career as a
politician, soldier and diplomat: never as a poet. It is
possible that 'art' in this poem means something different
from poetry, though there is no indication what that could
be. More likely, I may be over-interpreting - this is a bit
of a try-on, I admit.

