&quot;outcast state&quot; could simply mean that he is *feeling* alienated from
society, not that he has been banished. The &quot;travel&quot; of 27 and 28
does not seem to be irremediable. The poet, in 28, indeed
contemplates his &quot;return&quot;; as far as my perhaps benighted
comprehension goes, there is no sense either there or in its
travel-mate 27 of anything preventing his return beyond the simple
necessities of carrying out some personal task or responsibility. Nor
do I get any feeling of &quot;no sense of direction.&quot; Quite the opposite,
the fact that, as we see in 28, he is toiling successively farther
suggests to me a linear progression with a definite, if distant,
destination; had he indeed *no* sense of direction, the idea of
increasing distance would be, as it were, more remote, and he'd be
whining about the aimlessness of his wandering. Further, if the poet
means us to derive an understanding of some sort of official
banishment due to &quot;disgrace,&quot; vis-a-vis &quot;outcast state,&quot; he certainly
fails to give us any clue as to the circumstances or location of this
what would have had to have been an extremely important life event.
And &quot;overwhelming grief&quot;? Mon dieu, a sensitive poetic soul is just
unhappy about being away from his much beloved friend for a while.
The fact that a poet might feel something deeply and express himself
vividly about it doesn't mean that the actual event rises--beyond the
poet's momentary feelings, and our own in empathy--to any level of
significance.

***Given--even considering Fortune and men's eyes--the wide
application of &quot;disgrace&quot; and &quot;outcast state&quot; (&quot;Fred, did you see Will
