but relatively minor ones. The character
of Oxford is well-known, as are the major
events in his life, his loves and hates, and
his rivals at court. All these are revealed
in the sonnets. Perhaps the most
surprising revelations are that he was so
precocious, that his relationship with the
Queen was so close, and that their shared
sense of humour was so earthy. But these
are only surprising at first glance. The
broad outlines of these facts are either in
the historical record, or can be inferred by
a little thought. For example, it is obvious
