How to be made to look stupid in one easy lesson.
Curse you, Gary Kosinsky!

HOWEVER (You didn't really think I'd let it go at that
did you?)...

It is certainly very unusual for Shakespeare to use
the word in this sense. After another browse, I have
managed to find only a couple more fairly clear ones,
both from *Pericles*:

From the dejected state wherein he is
He hopes by you his fortunes yet may flourish.

and

Sir, 'tis the governor of Mytilene,
Who, hearing of your melancholy state,
Did come to see you.

In both of these cases, however, a word is added which
makes it *clear* that it is a mental state being meant.
Similarly, the word as used in line 10 of the Sonnet
clearly refers to the mental state he has already been
talking about - &quot;myself almost despising&quot;.

The nearest definition to this use that I can find in
the OED is I.2.a. &quot;a condition (of mind or feeling); the
mental or emotional condition in which a person finds
himself at a particular time&quot;. None of the illustrations
of this lacks such an indication either.

The first definition(s) offered for 'state' in the OED
are as follows:

I. Condition, manner of existing.
1. a. A combination of circumstances or
attributes belonging for the time being to a
person or thing; a particular manner or way of
existing, as defined by the presence of certain
circumstances or attributes; a condition.

This certainly seems to be the one that best fits the
use in line 2 of the Sonnet, which is indeed given as
an illustration of it. His condition is that of being
cast out, he is an outcast. Only if the associated
word had been 'downcast', for example, rather than
'outcast', would any indication of his feelings come
into *that particular phrase*. In other words &quot;My
outcast state of mind&quot; doesn't mean anything.

What this does, of course, is to give us a very nice
illustration of Robert's observation that Shakespeare
tends to change the meaning of any word that he uses
more than once in close proximity.

In this Sonnet, he uses the word 'state' three times.

1) The first, as Buffalo and I have been arguing, is
his condition, or manner of existing, as an outcast,
whatever he means by that.

2) The second is indeed his mental state, but (as
Paul and Lynne have suggested) almost certainly has
within it thoughts of sexual arousal. The appropriate
definition for that concerns the &quot;physical condition&quot;
of something (for which I quite liked one of the
illustrations, related to the &quot;state of the moon, as
well when he is somewhat increased..as also when he
is in the wane&quot;.)

3) The third, whilst returning to his condition as in
the first meaning, brings in yet another aspect of
'state' too - the idea of (II) &quot;Status; high rank;
pomp&quot; as possessed by Kings.

Interesting.

